00:37.120 --> 00:38.840
And here are your hosts.

00:43.900 --> 00:52.180
This is David Carson. And David Crews. Few characters in either science fiction
or fantasy have been as fascinating to readers as Conan the Barbarian. Conan is

00:52.180 --> 01:00.180
the creation of Robert E. Howard, a writer of the 1930s who lived in Cross
Plains, Texas. Howard filled the pulp magazines of his day with westerns,

01:00.340 --> 01:07.960
detective stories, horror stories, science fantasy, just about anything that
would sell. But he became best known for his tales of heroic fantasy,

01:08.300 --> 01:17.060
particularly the ones that involved Conan. Conan was a giant barbarian who lived
a swashbuckling life in the mythical Hyborian age that Howard created. There is

01:17.060 --> 01:26.160
nothing fancy or subtle about Conan. He survives and flourishes by pure muscle
and swordplay. Howard's writing was colorful and exciting and perfectly matched

01:26.160 --> 01:26.660
his hero.

01:32.620 --> 01:41.200
Howard committed suicide in 1936 at the age of 30. He left a number of
unfinished Conan manuscripts and story ideas. And the character of Conan was so

01:41.200 --> 01:49.800
appealing to readers that authors have recently been writing new material on him
or finishing Howard's own incomplete stories. Noted science fiction and fantasy

01:49.800 --> 01:57.780
author L. Sprague de Camp has written Conan stories and become interested enough
in Howard's life to write a biography of him. We asked de Camp if Howard was

01:57.780 --> 02:07.340
anything like Conan. Well, everybody knows that Conan is an idealization of
Howard. In other words, the kind of person that Howard thought he would have

02:07.340 --> 02:23.780
liked to have been the ruthless, domineering, footloose, irresponsible
adventurer. Actually, Robert was no respecter of laws and regulations. But the

02:23.780 --> 02:34.500
key word here is idealization. De Camp says Howard and Conan were nothing alike.
Actually, Robert was just the opposite type. Except for hot tempers and

02:34.500 --> 02:50.440
chivalrous attitude toward women, they had nothing in common. Robert Howard was
shy, bookish, compassionate, extremely polite,

02:55.700 --> 03:09.920
and socially timid, and so law-abiding that he wouldn't cut across the
neighbor's lot even, although everybody else across the lanes did. He was just

03:09.920 --> 03:20.680
about as different from the character Conan in the stories as a person could be.
De Camp believes Howard yearned to live in a past age, some more heroic time

03:20.680 --> 03:32.000
than the present. Well, Robert was always talking a lot about how he wished that
he thought he'd have been, really in his element, if he'd been born on the Texan

03:32.000 --> 03:44.400
frontier in the 19th century, or in some barbarian society like the ancient
Gauls or Goths or somebody. Well, I don't, I think he'd have had a very

03:44.400 --> 03:57.760
unpleasant surprise. Because it wasn't, it wasn't his temperament at all. He was
a, he was a shy, bookish introvert. Finally, De Camp reveals that Howard had a

03:57.760 --> 04:09.440
serious mental problem. He had an outsized monkey on his back, and he was, he
was doomed from some way back. He planned his suicide ever since he was a little

04:09.440 --> 04:19.460
boy. He told his mother when he was a little kid even, Mama, when you
die, I want to die with you. And the foolish woman, I think, probably sort of

04:19.460 --> 04:28.900
giggled and encouraged him. It was long planned, and several people knew about
it. But they didn't do anything. The only thing you could have done with Robert

04:28.900 --> 04:38.260
was, if you'd gotten him to a good shrink early enough, quite a good many years
before he actually killed himself, why, something might have been done. But

04:38.260 --> 04:49.580
that, of course, is uncertain. Howard wrote some 21 Conan stories, most of which
appeared in Weird Tales in the 1930s. Only one novel, Conan the Conqueror, was

04:49.580 --> 04:54.240
published, and that was some time after Howard's death. More next time about
Robert E. Howard.

