06:01.660 --> 06:05.680
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

06:21.620 --> 06:27.100
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

06:29.760 --> 06:31.520
And here are your hosts.

06:36.160 --> 06:44.660
This is David Crews and David Carson. There are subcategories coming under the
general headings of science fiction and fantasy. One of the most popular these

06:44.660 --> 06:53.380
days is heroic fantasy. It's sometimes called sword and sorcery, a term that
almost serves as a definition for the genre. It deals with heroic barbarians

06:53.380 --> 07:02.180
swinging large bloody swords and sorcerers conjuring up all manner of demons.
And as we've said, it's popular nowadays, particularly the Conan stories of

07:02.180 --> 07:11.960
Robert E. Howard. We asked an authority on heroic fantasy, L. Sprague de Camp, to
tell us why the form is so fascinating to readers. I think that part of the

07:11.960 --> 07:30.900
popularity of the genre was a reaction to certain trends in fiction following
the Second World War, such as the fondness for heavily subjective psychological

07:30.900 --> 07:35.640
or psychiatric stories,

07:35.960 --> 07:50.680
very sentimental stories, stories glorifying the little man, the anti-hero, that
hopeless little jerk who can't do anything right and who has no brains or brawn

07:50.680 --> 08:01.320
or character and whose only function is to suffer and suffer. Well, I think
people got sort of tired of that after a while. So they then, between the

08:01.320 --> 08:12.240
paperback publication of the Conan stories, for which I can claim the credit,
I'm the one who sold them, and the paperback publication of Tolkien's Lord of

08:12.240 --> 08:26.640
the Rings, which was the other major factor in launching this boom, why that got
people to reading heroic fantasy on a large scale, which they are still doing.

08:37.840 --> 08:45.440
De Camp has written his own sword and sorcery, but he's also worked on the Conan
material of Robert E. Howard. He tells us how he was introduced to Howard's

08:45.440 --> 08:59.260
stories of Conan. ...York in, uh, it was around the end of 1950, and, uh, let me
see, I think it was, uh, I think it was a naval war game at Pratt's apartment or

08:59.260 --> 09:09.880
something. No, it wasn't. It was a party at Pratt's apartment. And, uh, he
handed me a copy of Conan the Conqueror, found in hardback, published by Gnome

09:09.880 --> 09:19.660
Press. And he said, here, take this along. I think you might find it
interesting. I don't care much for it myself, but who knows? So I took it. It

09:19.660 --> 09:29.760
seems that, uh, Martin had, um, by inadvertence sent, uh, Fletcher two review
copies, and Fletcher gave me one. So I started reading it on the train going

09:29.760 --> 09:40.280
home and was hooked right away. Kept on until I'd read the thing through, and
then I read it through again. Howard died in the 1930s, but De Camp became so

09:40.280 --> 09:49.260
involved with the character of Conan that he started to edit some of Howard's
papers and to write his own Conan stories. And then a year later, I found some,

09:49.440 --> 10:04.620
I learned about some unpublished Conan manuscripts in the custody of, uh, the
agent for the Howard Literary Estate. And, uh, I read them, and arrangements

10:04.620 --> 10:15.960
were made with the Howard Ayers and, uh, the agent for me to edit them for
public, and arrange for publication, and on, things have, uh, things have gone

10:15.960 --> 10:19.340
on, uh, on and on, and build up from that.

10:27.100 --> 10:35.960
De Camp has written original Conan material, but he's also finished incomplete
Howard stories and edited others. De Camp is also technical advisor to a movie

10:35.960 --> 10:44.760
on Conan that will premiere this week. It's entitled Conan the Barbarian, and it
will show you what heroic fantasy is all about. More about Robert E. Howard next

10:44.760 --> 10:45.060
time.

