11:48.480 --> 11:52.420
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

12:08.240 --> 12:13.640
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

12:16.300 --> 12:18.040
And here are your hosts.

12:23.000 --> 12:31.060
This is David Carson. And David Crews. Robert E. Howard, the creator of Conan the
Barbarian, was a paradox. He was brought up on the arid plains of west central

12:31.060 --> 12:39.820
Texas, lived in the small country town of Cross Plains, and hardly did any
traveling, and he died by his own hand at the age of 30. Yet Howard wrote heroic

12:39.820 --> 12:47.140
stories that were set in the mythical age after the fall of Atlantis. He was
fascinated with the misty, cold northern landscape in which he set his tales.

12:47.720 --> 12:56.180
Conan, his greatest creation, was a barbarian from the north, a giant who strode
across the Hyborian age wielding a bloody broadsword. But Howard's life was a

12:56.180 --> 13:05.420
quiet one. He was introverted, bookish, and shy. As far as we know, he was never
in a brawl or fight of any kind. Why did Howard create Conan and place him in a

13:05.420 --> 13:14.520
mythical northern landscape? What sort of mind would conceive of a barbarian
hero, a loner who spurned civilization? We spoke with Dr. Charlotte Laughlin, a

13:14.520 --> 13:22.260
professor at Howard Payne University in Brownwood, Texas, not far from Howard's
home in Cross Plains. Dr. Laughlin is intimate with Howard's life and has done

13:22.260 --> 13:30.980
research for her Howard biography. She believes there are some reasons for
Howard's obsession with Conan. I think that, again, it was a sort of explanation

13:30.980 --> 13:41.000
for why he did not fit in with other people. He liked to believe, I am the last
barbarian. It's because, and my type will prevail. He liked to believe that the

13:41.000 --> 13:49.580
other people had a veneer of civilization on them that got them away from the
basics that were really important. And if you've read his correspondence with

13:49.580 --> 14:01.000
Lovecraft, they had long arguments about the physical versus the intellectual
needs of a society. And Howard would say that in the tough country where he

14:01.000 --> 14:10.880
lived, you had to be physically fit. And he spent a great deal of his life, his
adult life, trying to be physically fit, boxing and working out and that sort of

14:10.880 --> 14:11.100
thing.

14:17.580 --> 14:26.100
Howard also was fascinated with the legendary past of Britain, especially with
the savage Picts and the early heroes of Celtic myth. Some of his Conan stories,

14:26.260 --> 14:35.360
such as Across the Dark River, have ancient Britain as their setting. We asked
Dr. Laughlin why Howard was so drawn to this material. He claimed that he was

14:35.360 --> 14:43.700
full-blood Irish and they were the Irish kings like some other people we know
claim to be. But there's no evidence that he certainly was not full-blood Irish.

14:43.860 --> 14:54.020
People have traced his genealogy. But this was part of his image of himself. He
was trying to project other people and trying to create for himself. There

14:54.020 --> 15:04.920
again, he wrote at one time that he wrote about the barren, cold, windswept,
damp areas even though he lived here. I think that again might be a sort of wish

15:04.920 --> 15:12.720
fulfillment. Who wouldn't like to be someplace where it's cold on a day like
this? He wanted to be away from where he was because I don't think we can

15:12.720 --> 15:25.800
underestimate the anger and frustration that was boiling around in Robert Howard
all the time. I see it in all of his poetry and a great deal of his fiction.

15:26.760 --> 15:35.080
Cross Plains neighbors say that he had a, there was a big tree stump out by his
yard and I believe it was a sledgehammer not an axe. And sometimes in the middle

15:35.080 --> 15:41.540
of the day he would go out there, you know, and you could just see that he was
so tense and he would take that sledgehammer and he would just wham it and wham

15:41.540 --> 15:51.400
it and wham it on this tree stump. That a tremendous amount of anger he didn't
fit in with other people. He wanted to be somewhere else so he wrote about

15:51.400 --> 15:54.120
something that was like nothing he had experienced.

16:01.120 --> 16:10.120
Howard wrote reams of fantasy in the pulp era of the 1930s, most of it for Weird
Tales. We asked Dr. Laughlin why Howard wrote fantasy. Did he have the talent to

16:10.120 --> 16:17.880
write more realistic fiction that might have gotten him out of the pulp ghetto?
He may have had the talent but I certainly don't believe he was capable of

16:17.880 --> 16:26.660
writing realistic fiction. He was not that closely tied to reality himself. I
don't believe he ever could have written realistic novels. He had to write

16:26.660 --> 16:31.060
fantasies of some sort. More about Robert E. Howard next time.

16:38.040 --> 16:46.000
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

16:46.000 --> 16:52.340
Odessa, Texas. 

