18:11.600 --> 18:12.820
This is David Crews.

18:13.120 --> 18:13.780
And David Carson.

18:14.300 --> 18:20.700
Fantasy writer Robert E. Howard grew up in the 1920s and the 1930s in the small Texas town of Cross Plains.

18:21.100 --> 18:24.600
But he wasn't like other small town boys. He kept to himself quite a bit.

18:24.600 --> 18:32.240
He read a lot and used a vivid imagination to create his memorable heroic fantasies, for most of which are the stories of Conan the Barbarian.

18:32.920 --> 18:37.500
Howard died in 1936, but some of the people in Cross Plains still remember him clearly.

18:38.080 --> 18:44.860
We spoke with two of Howard's friends, Jack Scott, the editor of the Cross Plains newspaper, and Leroy Butler, Howard's next door neighbor.

18:45.380 --> 18:51.100
Butler remembers a time when he and Howard were still children and they bought some swords from a mail order company in New York.

18:52.120 --> 18:58.960
But we ordered those things and we'd get out in the backyard and wrap a band down a hamster around our hedge-like pirate.

19:00.260 --> 19:03.480
And we'd get out fence with those things.

19:04.260 --> 19:09.960
Of course we didn't dare, you know, hit each other with them because they were, they'd have gone through you.

19:11.840 --> 19:19.900
But we did that quite a bit. We had an immense live oak tree in our backyard and we'd get out there and shade that oak tree in.

19:22.780 --> 19:33.360
Pretend that we were back maybe in the dark ages or something or in the time of the Spanish man.

19:34.880 --> 19:40.800
Things like that. He had things like that on his mind all the time.

19:41.140 --> 19:44.400
Butler says that Robert was a loner dedicated to his writing.

19:45.420 --> 19:48.560
Robert never married. He never seemed interested in girls.

19:51.740 --> 19:58.560
And he did have one girlfriend there in Cross Plains for a time. I'd see him out in the car driving around once in a while.

19:59.420 --> 20:01.620
But I don't think that lasted long.

20:02.420 --> 20:07.400
He was just wrapped up in his, in his work writing those stories.

20:09.480 --> 20:15.860
And he had a blast-in-back porch on the southeast side of the house there.

20:17.520 --> 20:20.620
And it wasn't too far from my mother's bedroom.

20:22.460 --> 20:28.500
And a lot of times at night he'd wake her up with that typewriter clock in, you know, at 1 or 2 o'clock in the morning.

20:28.500 --> 20:36.480
Some inspiration. He'd probably be laying there in bed and think of something and he'd get up and write it down right quick.

20:39.360 --> 20:41.280
And he just worked all hours.

20:42.400 --> 20:55.300
Jack Scott also comments on Howard's unusual personality. Howard was a little on
the odd side. He wasn't intimate with very many people. He was rather aloof. But

20:55.300 --> 21:07.900
he was a big, robust man. To me, he was a combination of Edgar Allen Poe and
Jack London, if you can imagine that two together. In 1936, when Howard's mother

21:07.900 --> 21:19.420
was dying of a terminal illness, Howard took his own life. I remember the
morning he killed himself very well. I heard on the street that Robert Howard

21:19.420 --> 21:30.640
had just shot himself. I immediately jumped in my car and ran down there and got
down there. A few neighbors had gathered. It wasn't generally known over the

21:30.640 --> 21:42.540
town, but the old justice of the peace was standing there on the gallery, the
front porch. When I walked up, he called me and said, Come here, Jack. And I

21:42.540 --> 21:53.580
stepped up there and he took me into the bedroom. And he pointed to an old
Underwood typewriter. It had four lines written on it there. And Howard had,

21:54.020 --> 22:06.620
when he had been told that his mother wouldn't live throughout the day, he went
to this typewriter, wrote these four lines, walked outside, sat down in his car

22:06.620 --> 22:17.740
and shot his head off. And this old JP asked me what these four lines meant.
They said, I'm sure you've read them. All fled, all done, so lift me on the pyre.

22:17.900 --> 22:23.600
The feast is over. The lamps expire. More about Robert E. Howard next time.

